Date: 0/0/1845
Source: New Zealand (Selwyn)
Author: SELWYN
Vol / Page: Part II (Church in the Colonies VII) 32
Edition:
Quote: A small native village is here [at Ohinemutu], with the usual appurtenances of a native steam kitchen at the hot springs; namely, hot plates, made of large slabs of stone, laid over boiling water ... steam hanghis, or native ovens, always in readiness ... A native swing completes the equipment of this fashionable watering place ...
Notes: 1843 Oct 30 Selwyn Journal in 1845 NZ Part II (Church in the Colonies VII)

Date: 0/0/1847
Source: Savage Life
Author: ANGAS
Vol / Page: 1/298
Edition:
Quote: On one occasion, when on a visit to one of the missionaries at Waimate, a fine gander attracted his [sc. Waka Nene's] attention, and he secretly ordered it to be seized, and prepared for his dinner in a native oven; ... <i>Ibid.</i> 2/125 ... Newman [was] busily engaged in cooking ... the pig, in a native oven in the ground between hot stones.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1849
